      "type": "ValidationResult",
      "name": "Pump pressure rise validation across 5 operating points",
      "description": "CFD-predicted differential pressure compared against bench measurements at 5 flow-speed combinations (2–6 L/min, 2000–3000 RPM). Maximum relative error is 6.8% at the low-flow high-speed condition. Monte Carlo propagation of inlet flow rate uncertainty (±3%) and rotational speed uncertainty (±15 RPM) was performed at the campaign level; the resulting pressure rise uncertainty band (±4.1%) partially overlaps experimental scatter.",
      "comparisonMetric": "Maximum relative error: 6.8%; mean relative error: 3.2%",
      "agreementAssessment": "Acceptable for pressure performance characterization",
      "hasUncertaintyQuantification": "https://uofa.net/synth/uq/monte-carlo-pressure-rise-propagation"
    },
    {
      "id": "https://uofa.net/synth/validation/vr-hemolysis-index-bench",
      "type": "ValidationResult",
      "name": "Normalized index of hemolysis (NIH) bench validation — 4 conditions",
      "description": "CFD-predicted normalized index of hemolysis compared against in-vitro hemolysis measurements using the modified hemolysis index protocol. Predictions use the power-law Giersiepen-Wurzinger model. Ratio of predicted to measured NIH ranges from 0.61 to 1.44 across 4 conditions, indicating substantial scatter. The assessment narrative notes that donor blood variability introduces aleatory uncertainty estimated at ±25% on measured NIH values; however, this estimate is not formally encoded as a UQ artifact linked to this validation result.",
      "comparisonMetric": "Predicted/measured NIH ratio range: 0.61–1.44",
      "agreementAssessment": "Marginal — scatter exceeds acceptable band for absolute hemolysis claim"
    },
    {
      "id": "https://uofa.net/synth/validation/vr-wall-shear-stress-distribution",
      "type": "ValidationResult",
      "name": "Wall shear stress distribution comparison — impeller blade passages",
      "description": "High-shear regions identified by CFD (>150 Pa) are compared against micro-PIV measurements in scaled blade passage model. Spatial extent of high-shear zone agrees within 12% of measured area. Grid sensitivity analysis (3-level Richardson extrapolation) provides discretization uncertainty estimate of ±8% on peak WSS. Formal UQ node linked.",
      "comparisonMetric": "High-shear zone area agreement: 12% relative difference; peak WSS discretization uncertainty: ±8%",
      "agreementAssessment": "Adequate for shear topology identification",
      "hasUncertaintyQuantification": "https://uofa.net/synth/uq/richardson-extrapolation-wss-discretization"
    },
    {
